Swallowed by the stars :) Me by @kimhenry.dance on a freezing night. I'm currently editing the pictures from that special night so @m.abrahamercado gets good content for the video he's going to make this week. It's been a few months since we went there and everything went so fast that I forgot part of it. Seeing the images reminded me how harsh the conditions were and how hard we kicked our asses to shoot late at night below freezing point. On this specific picture, I didn't remove my jacket to look cool for the picture. I was sweating due to the fact that we were shooting uphill using a 85mm lens. I ran like crazy back and forth to do the light-painting and then validate/re-frame. This was the last shot before going back to our van where we spent the night. #bestlifeever

photo.title: Light-painting at the Uyuni salt flats

description._content: This was created a week ago, but our skin still has that salty taste of that magical place. The salt flat of Uyuni in Bolivia is by far the largest of its kind. 100 times bigger than the ones in Utah near Salt Lake City. It's not an easy location, but the rewards are incredible. It's much much crazier than any picture you might have seen :) Lit by hand in one second using a plastic tube, a feather, and a flashlight. ... but things are not always going well. Yesterday night we created barely nothing because of the high wind, and this morning... ahh this morning... here's the story: we had an appointment with the full moon at 5:30am to shoot with it at 800mm (remember our giant moon from death valley, episode 30 youtu.be/SvWUkA1s_D8 ). The thing is that this was our main reason to go back in #uyuni (a third time!). We won't get that alignment for years (full moon set during the blue hour during the wet season). Things were looking great, the moon was glorious when the alarm clock rang at 4am. We were really well prepared, but right before we hit the peak moment, the moon disapeared behind a thick cloud just above the horizon. We still have a chance tomorrow but the light is going to be very different. So we decided to go back to #lightpainting instead and we created this picture. Notice how Kim is bright. That's because we did this shot opposite to the sunrise With Kim Henry TubeStories.tv AboutTheTubes.com

Behind the scenes: youtu.be/4rILcmJ1W10 A few lost facts about episode 50: 1) we did shoot giant sunset, moonrise, sunrise and moonset, but we could have done light-painting at sunset too. We failed to do so because we focussed on something we've never done before: a giant moonset. It turned out to be much later than what we expected (we're not 100% competent with @photopills yet, but we know where we failed). That means that we would have plenty of time to do a light-painting session between the sunset and the moonrise (you can clearly see that from the youtube video). 2) we were at the same exact spot two days earlier, and our friend @kelleywjohnson was with us (episode 42). That night would have gave us a much better alignment and he knew it. I decided to keep with the original plan (light-painting) and so we did. But he's the one that made me think a lot and we ended up going there by ourselves after he left. (THANK YOU KELLEY!). 3) The desert at sunrise is the most quiet thing i've ever experimented. M-A-G-I-C-A-L. 4) This picture is created at sunrise. This is something we don't do often but there's something so special about it as we're never sure if we're doing a good framing, we're cold, and them boom, the whole scene starts to reveal itself as the sun goes up. Wow
When everything aligns perfectly.... sunset, moonrise, sunrise and moonset. All done within the same night. Behind the scenes and how to create these images: youtu.be/4rILcmJ1W10

New video tutorial!!! youtu.be/-lkjChUqksc In this episode, I'm answering that famous question about the stars and the Milky Way. I used to do composites (my early works), but all of my actual work is single frame. Of course, some editing is involved mostly for the Milky Way (check out for Michael Shainblum tutorials to figure it out), but I managed to get everything in one frame by using some very simple tricks. This is what I explain in this video. Thanks Kelley Johnson for your help on this one --- About the Tube Stories We're a dancer/photographer duo making our way using a tube, a feather, and a flashlight. Everything we do is lit by hand, one frame at a time. Light-painting for us is a lifestyle, and this is what we share with our audience. The purpose of the Tube Stories is to bring a brighter and more colorful night to whoever is going to cross our path. Our work has been presented on the BBC, CNN, MTV, VICE, TEDx and much more. --- About Eric Paré (Instagram: @ericparephoto) Eric Paré is an artist-entrepreneur. When he's not on the road creating the Tube Stories, he can be found with his team at his studios in Montréal where he is working on multi-camera concepts and new technologies. He has recently been doing high ends projects for Intel, HP, Facebook, Microsoft and Adobe. --- About Kim Henry (Instagram: @kimhenry.dance) Kim Henry is a professional contemporary dancer that has a fascination for movement and human being. Versatile and curious, she seeks for projects that push her beyond her limits. As a freelance artist, she took part in more than 45 dance and physical theater projects since 2011. From a stage in a full-house theater to an empty desert, dancing is the language she likes the most. Follow us on instagram: instagram.com/kimhenry.dance - instagram.com/ericparephoto

Last episode of the Bahamas series is out! youtu.be/Eosfgrjg4mA And we finally did it! We've been talking about doing sunrise light-painting for so long, and it's during this trip that we've made it for the first time. The challenge here is to get set up properly before the blue hour, which can be tricky as we don't see exactly what's going to be revealed by the first glow of the day. It turned out to be much greater than I expected. The vibe of the morning is so different, and the colors were totally out of this world. To this day, this is one of my most favorite moment. The connection we get, the simplicity of the surroundings and the results are exactly what the Tube Stories are about. At the beginning of the video, you'll see our two first sunrise light-painting (January 21st without the clouds, and January 22nd with the cotton ball clouds) My favorite flashlight: amzn.to/2xDGn9d Tubes and gear: ericpare.com/gear If you are interested to know more about tube light-painting, check out our learning group: fb.com/groups/ericpare --- About the Tube Stories We're a dancer/photographer duo making our way using a tube, a feather, and a flashlight. Everything we do is lit by hand, one frame at a time. Light-painting for us is a lifestyle, and this is what we share with our audience. The purpose of the Tube Stories is to bring a brighter and more colorful night to whoever is going to cross our path. Our work has been presented on the BBC, CNN, MTV, VICE, TEDx and much more. --- About Eric Paré (Instagram: @ericparephoto) Eric Paré is an artist-entrepreneur. When he's not on the road creating the Tube Stories, he can be found with his team at his studios in Montréal where he is working on multi-camera concepts and new technologies. He has recently been doing high ends projects for Intel, HP, Facebook, Microsoft and Adobe. --- About Kim Henry (Instagram: @kimhenry.dance) Kim Henry is a professional contemporary dancer that has a fascination for movement and human being. Versatile and curious, she seeks for projects that push her beyond her limits. As a freelance artist, she took part in more than 45 dance and physical theater projects since 2011. From a stage in a full-house theater to an empty desert, dancing is the language she likes the most. howto: fb.com/groups/ericpare instagram.com/kimhenry.dance instagram.com/ericparephoto This is another light-painting created at the crocodile pond on Holbox island, Mexico. This is not the name of the place, but on our third night there, we saw a map and there was a crocodile sign on it. So we googled and found out that the island was full of crocodiles. We went there anyway as we didn't hear anything from the 2 previous nights, but ... ah.... that was one of the scariest shooting we have ever made. Sometimes it's better to not know ;)

Sunset countdown. Invisible behind the clouds, but feeling it's presence. Dancing with Kim, following the waves one inch above the ocean water, touched by the entire connection between her movements, the sea and the clouds. Living together the transition from day to night one minute at a time, tasting each change of sun-to-earth choregraphy mood. Sliding on the gradient of the newborn night. Feeling the urge in an endless moment. It will be dark soon, we'll turn on the lights soon. With kimhenry.dance
